In mathematics, an '''Ockham algebra''' is a [[Bounded lattice|bounded]] [[distributive lattice]] with a dual [[endomorphism]]. They were introduced by {{harvtxt|Berman|1977}}, and were named after [[William of Ockham]] by {{harvtxt|Urquhart|1979}}. Ockham algebras form a [[variety (universal algebra)|variety]].

Examples of Ockham algebras include [[Boolean algebra]]s, [[De Morgan algebra]]s, [[Stone algebra]]s, and [[Kleene algebra (with involution)|Kleene algebra]]s.

