{{refimprove|date=July 2011}} '''Regularized canonical correlation analysis''' is a way of using [[ridge regression]] to solve the [[singularity theory|singularity]] problem in the [[cross-covariance matrix|cross-covariance matrices]] of [[canonical correlation analysis]]. By converting <math>\operatorname{cov}(X, X)</math> and <math>\operatorname{cov}(Y, Y)</math> into <math>\operatorname{cov}(X, X) + \lambda I_X</math> and <math>\operatorname{cov}(Y, Y) + \lambda I_Y</math>, it ensures that the above matrices will have reliable [[Matrix inverse|inverses]].
The idea probably dates back to [[Hrishikesh D. Vinod]]'s publication in 1976 where he called it "Canonical ridge".<ref>{{Cite journal | author = Hrishikesh D. Vinod | title = Canonical ridge and econometrics of joint production | journal = [[Journal of Econometrics]] | volume = 4 | issue = 2 |date=May 1976 | pages = 147–166 | doi = 10.1016/0304-4076(76)90010-5 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | author = [[Kanti Mardia]]| title = Multivariate Analysis |display-authors=etal}}</ref> It has been suggested for use in the analysis of [[functional neuroimaging]] data as such data are often singular.<ref>{{Cite journal |author1=Finn Årup Nielsen |author2=Lars Kai Hansen |author3=Stephen C. Strother | title = Canonical ridge analysis with ridge parameter optimization |date=May 1998 | journal = [[NeuroImage]] | volume = 7 | pages = S758
| url = http://www2.imm.dtu.dk/pubdb/views/edoc_download.php/4981/pdf/imm4981.pdf }}</ref> It is possible to compute the regularized canonical vectors in the lower-dimensional space.<ref>{{Cite thesis | author = Finn Årup Nielsen | year = 2001 | title = Neuroinformatics in Functional Neuroimaging | url = http://www2.imm.dtu.dk/pubdb/views/edoc_download.php/201/pdf/imm201.pdf | publisher = [[Technical University of Denmark]] }} Section 3.18.5</ref>
